\begin_layout Subsubsection
Markets with Growing Inventor Shares Experienced a Fall in Inventor Productivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: RegProd"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 presents the results of running (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: spec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) when the outcome is the average growth in output per worker per effective
 inventor.
 I use growth in annual output per worker provided by the Economic Census
 and average this measure over the five-year window starting in the Economic
 Census year, and I analogously build a measure of average effective inventors
 over the same period.
 Inventor productivity is then defined as average output per worker growth
 divided by average number of effective inventors.
 Both the outcome and the dependent variable are measured in percentage
 points.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: RegProd"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 reveals a negative and significant correlation between the increase in
 the number of effective inventors and inventor productivity, regardless
 of the independent variable employed and the sample restriction adopted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Starting from the upper panel of Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: RegProd"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the median change in the share of effective inventors over the period
 was 
\begin_inset Formula $.014\text{pp}$
\end_inset

, while the measure of effective inventors has a median of 2018.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Recall that effective inventors in each year are measured as the sum of
 inventor fixed-effects in each year, and therefore do not represent the
 simple count of inventors.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The coefficient for concentration in Column (4) implies a fall of 
\begin_inset Formula $.15\text{pp}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $-.005\times.014\text{pp}\times2018$
\end_inset

) in average annual labor productivity growth.
 This number decreases to 
\begin_inset Formula $-.28\text{pp}$
\end_inset

 when considering only sectors with positive growth in labor productivity,
 which accounted for the bulk of the increase in inventor shares.
 An alternative back-of-the-envelope computation, using the change in product
 market concentration to predict the change in inventor shares gives even
 starker results.
 Using the coefficient in Column (2) of Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: RegShInvHHI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

(a) and considering a median change in the HHI of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.002$
\end_inset

 yields an increase in the share of effective inventors in concentrating
 sectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.045\text{pp}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies a fall in average labor productivity implied by misallocation
 of 0.45pp.
 While these numbers might appear large considering the entirety of the
 economy, it is worth noting that my sample includes mainly manufacturing
 and retail sectors, which experienced a sizable reduction of 
\begin_inset Formula $2.73pp$
\end_inset

 in average annual productivity growth from 1997 to 2012, driven by a steep
 decline in output per worker growth in manufacturing.
 Therefore, the mechanism I propose would explain around 15 percent of the
 observed decrease in output per worker growth in these sectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The estimates in the lower panel of Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: RegProd"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, which uses the HHI instead the change in inventor shares as independent
 variable, imply even larger growth effects.
 Using the estimates in Column (2), a median HHI change of 0.02 and a median
 number of effective inventors of 1421 in sectors with growth in inventor
 shares implies a 
\begin_inset Formula $-0.78$
\end_inset

pp change in output per worker growth from misallocation, with a confidence
 interval ranging from 
\begin_inset Formula $-0.13$
\end_inset

pp to 
\begin_inset Formula $-1.45$
\end_inset

pp.
 The midpoint of these estimates would explain 
\begin_inset Formula $28.6\%$
\end_inset

 of the observed fall in output per worker growth over the sample period
 (
\begin_inset Formula $-2.73\text{pp}$
\end_inset

), with bounds ranging from 
\begin_inset Formula $4.8\%$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $53\%$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This last set of results further supports the hypothesis that defensive
 innovation increased in concentrating sectors.
 To protect their dominant position, firms engage in such R&D to thwart
 innovation by potential competitors.
 Similarly citing defensive innovation as a motive, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "argentePatentsProductsProduct2020a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 report that incumbent firms tend to register a large number of patents,
 but account for a small share of overall innovations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
